On Thu, Apr 5, 2012 at 1:55 PM, Markus Lanthaler
&lt;markus.lanthaler@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; The JSON-LD spec says &quot;RDF can be expressed using JSON-LD&quot;.. Is this a
&gt;&gt; requirement for JSON-LD? Or could you strip it down to bear minimum
&gt;&gt; and forfeit that capability?
&gt;
&gt; It is not a requirement but it was a goal to be able to be as expressive as
&gt; RDF. We currently have these special keywords in the spec:
&gt;
&gt; @context - to link JSON keys to IRIs,
&gt; @id - to denote what is an IRI,
&gt; @value and @language - to specify the language of a string (I18N),
&gt; @type - to denote the type of an object/property (this is probably the most
&gt; RDFish one),
&gt; and @container with possible values of @list and @set to describe whether an
&gt; array should be considered as list or as unordered set
&gt;
&gt; So there&#39;s really not that much in the end. Perhaps you could drop
&gt; @container with @list/@list but as most of the time arrays are used as sets
&gt; in JSON while the JSON spec defines them to be ordered we wanted to support
&gt; both and be explicit about what was meant buy the author. If you don&#39;t need
&gt; I18N you could also drop @language - but since some of us are from Europe
&gt; (me included) we decided to support it as it is quite important in a lot of
&gt; use cases.
&gt;
&gt; What do you think could/should be dropped? I would really appreciate to hear
&gt; your opinion on that.
&gt;

I can&#39;t see any ways to pick apart JSON-LD to make it significantly
simpler (logically or aesthetically) because its whole design has been
affected by its goal of being &#39;as expressive as RDF&#39;. Sorry I can&#39;t be
more specific than that, I just can&#39;t see how you can solve that
problem.

I have some more questions for you, if that&#39;s alright:

Is something like hal+json Linked Data?

Do you agree that hal+json is simpler than JSON-LD?

Is there anything about hal+json that you consider insufficient or
&#39;wrong&#39; as a means to expose a REST application to machines?

